Locked architectural decisions
Decision is immutable

Once produced by policy evaluation, a Decision never changes.

A Decision has only two outcomes
APPROVED
REJECTED

There are no intermediate decision states such as:

PENDING
REVIEW
PROCESSING

Those belong to the Business Transaction or Execution lifecycle, not the Decision itself.

Override does not modify the Decision

If a human override occurs:

the original Decision remains unchanged;
the Override is recorded as a separate trust artifact;
both are preserved in the Execution Trust Record.
Policy is recorded with the Decision

The Decision records the exact Policy reference used during evaluation, ensuring deterministic replay and independent verification.

Canonical Principle (Locked)

A Decision is the immutable outcome of Policy evaluation.

It records what the Policy decided, not what was ultimately executed. Human Overrides and Executions are separate trust artifacts that build upon the Decision without altering it.


